    <div class="annotation">
      <h3>Attentiveness</h3>
      <p>Steps that use most or all of your attention should be marked as <strong>all attention</strong>. If it would be physically difficult to perform an identical task at the same time, then it most likely requires all of your attention. Examples include chopping vegetables, mixing ingredients, and stirring constantly.</p>
      <p>Steps that only require periodic or passive attention should be marked as <strong>some attention</strong>. Many steps using the burner, for example, requre you to keep an eye on the cooking food, occasionally stirring. This takes up some of your attention, but does not prevent you from doing other tasks at the same time.</p>
      <p><strong>No attention</strong> steps are those that a cook can completely ignore for the majority of their duration. Steps marked as none may use more attention during the first or last minute of the step, but if this higher attentiveness period is longer than a minute, the step should be broken up into multiple steps. Examples include preheating the oven, letting something stand, and boiling water.</p>
